.TH "PKGM" "8" "" "pkgm" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
pkgm \[em] declarative package and service manager
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]pkgm\f[R] \f[B]init\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]pkgm\f[R] \f[B]apply\f[R] [\f[B]\-n\f[R]|\f[B]\[en]dry\-run\f[R]]
.PP
\f[B]pkgm\f[R] \f[B]status\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]pkgm\f[R] \f[B]reset\f[R] [\f[I]NAME\f[R]\&...]
.PP
\f[B]pkgm\f[R] [\f[B]\-h\f[R]|\f[B]\[en]help\f[R]]
.PP
\f[B]pkgm\f[R] [\f[B]\-V\f[R]|\f[B]\[en]version\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]pkgm\f[R] is a declarative package and service manager driven by a
single \f[B]pkgm.toml\f[R] manifest.
It installs desired packages, removes obsolete ones, and manages
services \[em] with zero hardcoded package managers or init systems.
.PP
Configuration is read from \f[B]pkgm.toml\f[R], searched from the
current directory upward.
The desired state is compared against a previously saved manifest stored
in \f[B]\[ti]/.local/state/pkgm/\f[R].
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
\f[B]init\f[R]
Run interactive prompts defined in \f[B]prompts\f[R], save answers to
state cache.
Must be run at least once before \f[B]apply\f[R] if prompts are defined.
Re\-run to re\-answer prompts.
.TP
\f[B]apply\f[R]
Install desired packages and enable services defined in
\f[B]pkgm.toml\f[R].
Remove obsolete packages and disable services that were previously
installed but are no longer in the config.
.RS
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\[en]dry\-run\f[R]
Preview what would happen without making any changes.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R]
Show the current system state compared to the desired configuration.
Reports packages as \f[B]OK\f[R], \f[B]MISSING\f[R], \f[B]SKIP\f[R], or
\f[B]OBSOLETE\f[R], and services as \f[B]ENABLED\f[R],
\f[B]DISABLED\f[R], \f[B]SKIP\f[R], or \f[B]OBSOLETE\f[R].
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\[en]help\f[R]
Show usage information and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-V\f[R], \f[B]\[en]version\f[R]
Print program name and version, then exit.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Create \f[B]pkgm.toml\f[R] in your project or dotfiles repository.
Define managers under \f[B][managers]\f[R], then declare desired
packages and services under group sections matching the manager name.
.SS Manager definition
Each manager specifies shell commands for checking, installing,
removing, enabling, and disabling:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][managers.pacman]\f[R]
check   = \[dq]pacman \-Q {{.Name}}\[dq]
install = \[dq]sudo pacman \-S \-\-needed {{.Name}}\[dq]
remove  = \[dq]sudo pacman \-Rns {{.Name}}\[dq]

\f[B][managers.systemd]\f[R]
check   = \[dq]systemctl is\-enabled {{.Name}}\[dq]
enable  = \[dq]systemctl enable {{.Name}}\[dq]
disable = \[dq]systemctl disable {{.Name}}\[dq]
.EE
.PP
The \f[B]{{.Name}}\f[R] template variable is substituted with the
package or service name.
.SS Prompts
Interactive prompts store user preferences in state.
Values are available as \f[B]pref\f[R] conditions on packages and
services.
.IP
.EX
\f[B][prompts]\f[R]
laptop = { type = \[dq]bool\[dq], question = \[dq]Is this a laptop?\[dq] }
tablet = { type = \[dq]bool\[dq], question = \[dq]Do you use a tablet?\[dq] }
git_email = { type = \[dq]string\[dq], question = \[dq]Git email address\[dq] }
.EE
.PP
Types: \f[B]bool\f[R] (y/n), \f[B]string\f[R] (free text).
Values are cached in \f[B]\[ti]/.local/state/pkgm/\f[R] and reused
across runs.
Run \f[B]pkgm init\f[R] to re\-answer prompts.
.SS Package declaration
.IP
.EX
\f[B][pacman]\f[R]
packages = [\[dq]git\[dq], \[dq]zsh\[dq], \[dq]neovim\[dq]]
.EE
.PP
Per\-entry conditions are supported:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][pacman]\f[R]
packages = [
    \[dq]git\[dq],
    \[dq]{{ if .nvidia }}nvidia\-utils{{ end }}\[dq],
]
.EE
.SS Service declaration
.IP
.EX
\f[B][systemd]\f[R]
services = [\[dq]firewalld\[dq], \[dq]sshd\[dq]]
.EE
.SS Conditions
Package and service names can contain Go template expressions.
If a name renders to an empty string, the entry is skipped.
All prompt values are available as template variables:
.IP
.EX
\f[B][prompts]\f[R]
nvidia = { type = \[dq]bool\[dq], question = \[dq]Use NVIDIA config?\[dq] }

\f[B][pacman]\f[R]
packages = [
    \[dq]base\[dq],
    \[dq]{{ if .nvidia }}nvidia\-open{{ end }}\[dq],
]
.EE
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialize prompts interactively:
.IP
.EX
pkgm init
.EE
.PP
Declarative system upgrade:
.IP
.EX
cd \[ti]/projects/dotfiles
pkgm apply
.EE
.PP
Preview changes:
.IP
.EX
pkgm apply \-\-dry\-run
.EE
.PP
Check current state:
.IP
.EX
pkgm status
.EE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Error.
Common causes: unknown command, config parse failure, template error,
missing manager definition.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[B]\[ti]/.local/state/pkgm/*.toml\f[R]
Per\-directory manifest state files.
The filename is the SHA\-256 hash of the config directory path.
.SH SEE ALSO
